`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/run/` orchestrates one sandboxed subprocess execution end-to-end for `bwrap`-caged runs: PTY vs. plain-stdio dispatch, relay port readiness, controlling-terminal setup for interactive processes, and the post-run diagnostic surfaced to the user. Depending on this directory gets you the run entrypoint that a caller invokes once per caged command; internally it fans out into PTY session management, a relay-bind race guard, and diagnostic formatting.

The core cross-cutting fact is the `setsid --ctty --wait` fix (ADR-048): without it, a caged interactive process becomes a session leader with no controlling terminal, and Node-style processes busy-spin at 100% CPU polling `tcgetpgrp`. This constrains how the top-level module must invoke the child when a PTY is in play — it must launch through `setsid --ctty`, not a bare shell — and `tests.rs` pins this via real PTY + `/proc/self/stat` assertions rather than mocks, so a launch-command change here requires re-validating against that test.

`wait_for_relay_snippet`'s probe is `/proc/net/tcp`-based specifically to avoid `accept()`ing the relay's TCP connection, because `socat ...,fork` will forward a probing `accept()` straight to the host proxy and corrupt a real request; any change to the readiness probe must preserve this non-consuming behavior.

`pty/` supplies `run_on_pty`, whose `Ok(None)`/`Ok(Some(status))` distinction the top-level dispatch must handle to fall back to stdio inheritance correctly, and whose input-relay thread must be stopped on every exit path before stdio is reused. `tests/diagnostic.rs` locks the exact string format of `proxy_diagnostic`, so diagnostic-text changes and its assertions move together. No intent.md exists, so no divergence check is possible.